THE STUDENT PILOT REPORTED HE WAS PRACTICING NIGHT TOUCH AND GO 
LANDINGS ON RUNWAY 29 AT HIS HOME BASE AIRPORT.  HE STATED HE TOUCHED 
DOWN SHORT OF THE RUNWAY ON HIS SECOND LANDING.  THE AIRPLANE STRUCK A 
SNOWBANK AS IT CONTINUED TOWARDS THE RUNWAY.  THE MAIN LANDING GEAR 
SEPARATED AND THE AIRPLANE SKIDDED TO A STOP ON THE LEFT SIDE, FACING 
THE APPROACH END OF THE RUNWAY. 
THE STUDENT PILOT'S FAILURE TO MAINTAIN THE PROPER GLIDESLOPE. 
